But again, under
this system, they

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:43.620 align:middle line:84%
are sequestering
more carbon and are

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:46.650 align:middle line:84%
part of a natural cycle
that is actually beneficial.

00:28:46.650 --> 00:28:50.850 align:middle line:90%


00:28:50.850 --> 00:28:53.100 align:middle line:84%
Conventionally,
farmers, it's all

00:28:53.100 --> 00:28:56.050 align:middle line:84%
about keeping the grass
short in a vegetative state

00:28:56.050 --> 00:28:57.720 align:middle line:90%
so it's growing vigorously.

00:28:57.720 --> 00:28:59.730 align:middle line:84%
And that system
works while you're

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:02.640 align:middle line:84%
putting on lots of imported
fertilizers, particularly

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:05.610 align:middle line:84%
phosphate fertilizers,
largely from North Africa,

00:29:05.610 --> 00:29:08.760 align:middle line:84%
and a whole system that requires
digging up that fertilizer,

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:10.350 align:middle line:84%
and trucking it, and
then shipping it,

00:29:10.350 --> 00:29:12.840 align:middle line:84%
and then trucking it, and then
processing it, and then flying

00:29:12.840 --> 00:29:13.380 align:middle line:90%
it.

00:29:13.380 --> 00:29:15.547 align:middle line:84%
On the whole, it's a system
that's not going to work

00:29:15.547 --> 00:29:19.440 align:middle line:84%
and a future with
less fossil fuels.

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:26.070 align:middle line:90%


00:29:26.070 --> 00:29:27.740 align:middle line:84%
What we're doing
on the farm here

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:29.690 align:middle line:84%
is trying to reduce the
amount of fossil fuels

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:33.320 align:middle line:90%
that it takes to produce food.

00:29:33.320 --> 00:29:35.030 align:middle line:84%
We've got the
cattle going around.

00:29:35.030 --> 00:29:38.450 align:middle line:84%
We have hens following
along behind the cattle.

00:29:38.450 --> 00:29:40.190 align:middle line:84%
There's these pigs
on this farm too.

00:29:40.190 --> 00:29:42.920 align:middle line:84%
And we're milking
a few dairy cows.

00:29:42.920 --> 00:29:48.230 align:middle line:84%
And all that is really
about using a perennial crop

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:51.350 align:middle line:84%
like grass pasture with
forage from trees and that

00:29:51.350 --> 00:29:57.170 align:middle line:84%
around as well so we can produce
eggs from the chooks and pork

00:29:57.170 --> 00:30:01.100 align:middle line:84%
without relying on so
much of the annual grains

00:30:01.100 --> 00:30:03.850 align:middle line:84%
and all the energy that's
involved in producing them.

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:08.540 align:middle line:84%
So just trying to get the fossil
fuels out of our food system

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:12.290 align:middle line:84%
as much as we can and producing
healthy, natural food.

00:30:12.290 --> 00:30:18.320 align:middle line:90%


00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:21.050 align:middle line:84%
>> The powerful thing is that
with regenerative agriculture,

00:30:21.050 --> 00:30:23.630 align:middle line:84%
we can not only produce food
and we can not only produce

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:27.820 align:middle line:84%
an abundance of food, but we can
do it in a way that regenerates

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:30.830 align:middle line:84%
the land, that
replenishes the aquifers,

00:30:30.830 --> 00:30:33.590 align:middle line:84%
that sequesters carbon,
that nurtures and supports

00:30:33.590 --> 00:30:37.160 align:middle line:90%
biodiversity.

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:40.430 align:middle line:84%
Regenerative agriculture,
permaculture,

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:42.980 align:middle line:84%
holistic management-- there is
nothing magical about the way

00:30:42.980 --> 00:30:44.450 align:middle line:90%
that these things work.

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:46.850 align:middle line:84%
It's all based
upon sound science

00:30:46.850 --> 00:30:50.690 align:middle line:84%
and about having a
point of view that

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:53.300 align:middle line:84%
is looking at your
ecosystem in its entirety,

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:56.580 align:middle line:84%
not just individual
aspects of it.

00:30:56.580 --> 00:30:59.150 align:middle line:84%
So really what
this breaks down to

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:01.435 align:middle line:84%
is that anyone who's
looking after land,

00:31:01.435 --> 00:31:03.060 align:middle line:84%
whether you're a
farmer, or a gardener,

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:05.905 align:middle line:84%
whatever, you're an
ecosystem manager.

00:31:05.905 --> 00:31:28.440 align:middle line:90%


00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:31.590 align:middle line:84%
- My philosophy about
what to do in the world

00:31:31.590 --> 00:31:34.740 align:middle line:84%
isn't go to a pristine
area, and live there,

00:31:34.740 --> 00:31:36.270 align:middle line:90%
and enjoy your life.

00:31:36.270 --> 00:31:39.660 align:middle line:84%
It's to find a place that's
degraded and fix it up.

00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:46.430 align:middle line:90%


00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:48.830 align:middle line:84%
>> 23 years ago, we started
developing the food forest

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:51.230 align:middle line:90%
system here.

00:31:51.230 --> 00:31:55.060 align:middle line:84%
We've got 80 different species
of plants at last count.

00:31:55.060 --> 00:31:58.150 align:middle line:84%
Then that doesn't include the
80 different types of apples

00:31:58.150 --> 00:32:00.520 align:middle line:84%
and the 60 different
types of gooseberries.

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:02.870 align:middle line:84%
And that's lovely to
have that diversity.

00:32:02.870 --> 00:32:05.530 align:middle line:84%
And it means that every time
of the year there's thing's

00:32:05.530 --> 00:32:09.340 align:middle line:84%
flowering, things giving
fruit, crops you can eat.

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:10.800 align:middle line:84%
And so having
diversity is special.

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:13.695 align:middle line:84%
And that's what makes a
forest garden resilient.

00:32:13.695 --> 00:32:18.060 align:middle line:90%


00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:22.330 align:middle line:84%
This property had been
abandoned for probably 40 years.

00:32:22.330 --> 00:32:23.130 align:middle line:90%
No one lived here.

00:32:23.130 --> 00:32:24.990 align:middle line:84%
And an old house had
burnt down on the spot.

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:28.750 align:middle line:90%


00:32:28.750 --> 00:32:32.200 align:middle line:84%
>> In the top area, this area
where the house is now was

00:32:32.200 --> 00:32:37.180 align:middle line:84%
completely covered in junk and
the remains of the old house.

00:32:37.180 --> 00:32:39.400 align:middle line:84%
Most people would
have not even crossed

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:41.860 align:middle line:84%
the threshold of
the property to have

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:43.570 align:middle line:84%
a look at that I don't
think, because it

00:32:43.570 --> 00:32:44.695 align:middle line:90%
didn't look very appealing.

00:32:44.695 --> 00:32:48.225 align:middle line:84%
But to us, it did, because I
thought, well, for one thing,

00:32:48.225 --> 00:32:50.350 align:middle line:84%
nobody wants it so it's
probably going to be cheap,

00:32:50.350 --> 00:32:53.470 align:middle line:90%
and it was cheap to buy.

00:32:53.470 --> 00:32:55.210 align:middle line:84%
And secondly, I
thought I can fix this.

00:32:55.210 --> 00:32:58.850 align:middle line:90%


00:32:58.850 --> 00:33:02.950 align:middle line:84%
A food forest is a
permanent planting.

00:33:02.950 --> 00:33:05.140 align:middle line:84%
So you want to set up
just like a forest system.

00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:08.820 align:middle line:84%
So a forest system can be
the always the big trees,

00:33:08.820 --> 00:33:11.770 align:middle line:84%
and the little size trees, the
bottom layer, the ground layer.

00:33:11.770 --> 00:33:12.820 align:middle line:90%
They work together.

00:33:12.820 --> 00:33:15.740 align:middle line:84%
Some plants collect up some
minerals and give others back.

00:33:15.740 --> 00:33:17.323 align:middle line:84%
And the other one
does something else.

00:33:17.323 --> 00:33:20.460 align:middle line:90%


00:33:20.460 --> 00:33:23.520 align:middle line:84%
Growing out in the forest
garden there, aside

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:25.350 align:middle line:84%
from the native
trees which I've used

00:33:25.350 --> 00:33:28.840 align:middle line:84%
as a framework or a platform
for building everything else--

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.290 align:middle line:84%
and those provide me with
shelter from the wind

00:33:31.290 --> 00:33:33.400 align:middle line:84%
and also nest sites
for the birds.

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:36.450 align:middle line:84%
And the birds are a
really important player

00:33:36.450 --> 00:33:39.140 align:middle line:84%
in the management of the
garden and the cocoa,

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:42.060 align:middle line:84%
the cabbage trees that
I've got growing there,

00:33:42.060 --> 00:33:44.790 align:middle line:84%
starlings nest in
almost all of them.

00:33:44.790 --> 00:33:47.430 align:middle line:84%
And those starlings, as
they're feeding their youngers,

00:33:47.430 --> 00:33:49.830 align:middle line:84%
their babies are
flying out and finding

00:33:49.830 --> 00:33:52.410 align:middle line:84%
any soft-bodied
caterpillar or grub

00:33:52.410 --> 00:33:54.060 align:middle line:84%
they can so there's
our pest management

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:55.180 align:middle line:90%
for that kind of thing.

00:33:55.180 --> 00:33:58.020 align:middle line:90%


00:33:58.020 --> 00:34:00.680 align:middle line:84%
And then as an understory or
the second layer down to that,

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:03.800 align:middle line:84%
we have our fruit tree layer,
which is our heritage apples,

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:07.010 align:middle line:84%
and pears, and plums, and
, nectarines and peaches,

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:09.760 align:middle line:90%
apricots.

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:13.570 align:middle line:84%
And then below that a
layer of berry fruits,

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:16.750 align:middle line:84%
and currants, red currants,
black currants, white currants,

00:34:16.750 --> 00:34:19.210 align:middle line:84%
gooseberries,
worcesterberries, all

00:34:19.210 --> 00:34:23.440 align:middle line:84%
of those sorts of
shrubby plants that

00:34:23.440 --> 00:34:27.100 align:middle line:90%
like to grow in the semishade.

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:29.530 align:middle line:84%
And then wrapping
around all of that

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:33.130 align:middle line:84%
are the biennial and
perennial herbs, some of which

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:35.290 align:middle line:84%
are edible, some of
which are medicinal.

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:39.880 align:middle line:84%
And then below that there
are bulbs and root crops

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:44.440 align:middle line:84%
that grow, such as
parsnips, and wild carrots,

00:34:44.440 --> 00:34:46.150 align:middle line:90%
those kinds of things.

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:48.940 align:middle line:84%
And then winding their way
up through these things

00:34:48.940 --> 00:34:52.030 align:middle line:84%
are vines like grape
vines, and kiwi fruit,

00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:54.940 align:middle line:84%
and Manchurian gooseberries,
and hops, and all

00:34:54.940 --> 00:34:57.990 align:middle line:84%
sorts of things which kind
of bind everything together

00:34:57.990 --> 00:35:01.390 align:middle line:90%
and tie the forest together.

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:06.040 align:middle line:90%


00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:08.560 align:middle line:84%
>> It's so peaceful
when you walk about.

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:10.447 align:middle line:84%
And it's just the all
different flowers,

00:35:10.447 --> 00:35:11.530 align:middle line:90%
and the energy and action.

00:35:11.530 --> 00:35:13.643 align:middle line:84%
All the insects and the
birds have their own life.

00:35:13.643 --> 00:35:16.060 align:middle line:84%
And so the birds are doing all
their thing up in the trees

00:35:16.060 --> 00:35:17.185 align:middle line:90%
and coming down to feeding.

00:35:17.185 --> 00:35:20.020 align:middle line:84%
And insects are flying
around, and having babies,

00:35:20.020 --> 00:35:22.120 align:middle line:90%
and flying off on missions.

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:24.820 align:middle line:84%
It's like being in
another universe really.

00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:25.630 align:middle line:90%
It's just amazing.

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.520 align:middle line:84%
And it's, to me,
it's how life should

00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:29.980 align:middle line:84%
be with that livingness and
the interconnectedness of all

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:32.364 align:middle line:84%
the plants, and
bees, and the herbs.

00:35:32.364 --> 00:35:35.286 align:middle line:90%


00:35:35.286 --> 00:35:40.430 align:middle line:84%
>> In a forest garden like ours,
the major player is wildness,

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:43.610 align:middle line:84%
is the natural world and all
of those things that happen

00:35:43.610 --> 00:35:44.420 align:middle line:90%
in there.

00:35:44.420 --> 00:35:47.630 align:middle line:84%
And my job is just
to kind of mold

00:35:47.630 --> 00:35:50.020 align:middle line:84%
that to suit our purposes
to a certain extent.

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:53.860 align:middle line:90%


00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:56.620 align:middle line:84%
We are not separate
from the wild world.

00:35:56.620 --> 00:35:59.890 align:middle line:90%
We are as wild as it is.

00:35:59.890 --> 00:36:02.920 align:middle line:84%
But we've worked
towards a form that

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:06.790 align:middle line:84%
is not fitting in with the
wild world at all well.

00:36:06.790 --> 00:36:11.870 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to realign
us fairly soon, in my view,

00:36:11.870 --> 00:36:16.330 align:middle line:84%
unless we can recognize that
we need to be fully integrated

00:36:16.330 --> 00:36:18.250 align:middle line:90%
into that world.

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:29.660 align:middle line:90%


00:36:29.660 --> 00:36:31.510 align:middle line:84%
>> People in
indigenous societies,

00:36:31.510 --> 00:36:35.320 align:middle line:84%
in tribal societies or
in agrarian villages,

00:36:35.320 --> 00:36:40.570 align:middle line:84%
they were enmeshed in a matrix
of relationship that gave them

00:36:40.570 --> 00:36:42.130 align:middle line:90%
a strong identity.

00:36:42.130 --> 00:36:44.860 align:middle line:84%
Everybody who they
saw on a daily basis

00:36:44.860 --> 00:36:46.000 align:middle line:90%
knew them really well.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:49.800 align:middle line:90%


00:36:49.800 --> 00:36:53.690 align:middle line:84%
And we also were in intimate
connection with the land.

00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:54.590 align:middle line:90%
We knew every plant.

00:36:54.590 --> 00:36:55.760 align:middle line:90%
We knew every animal.

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:58.580 align:middle line:84%
Every bird we knew its
song, and when it sang,

00:36:58.580 --> 00:37:01.250 align:middle line:84%
and what bugs it ate, and
where those bugs lived,

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:03.430 align:middle line:84%
and what the soil smells
like where the bugs live,

00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:05.300 align:middle line:84%
and what plants grow there,
and what medicine the plants

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:06.350 align:middle line:90%
were used for.

00:37:06.350 --> 00:37:10.980 align:middle line:84%
We were in this
web of interbeing.

00:37:10.980 --> 00:37:15.860 align:middle line:84%
We felt as if we were
at home in the universe.

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:18.950 align:middle line:84%
That is missing in
our current society.

00:37:18.950 --> 00:37:21.740 align:middle line:84%
We're surrounded by a
sea of strangers, people

00:37:21.740 --> 00:37:24.880 align:middle line:84%
that we know only very
superficially if at all.

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:36.808 align:middle line:90%


00:37:36.808 --> 00:37:39.970 align:middle line:84%
For our people, the
ancestors and the land

00:37:39.970 --> 00:37:41.656 align:middle line:90%
are all part of one.

00:37:41.656 --> 00:37:43.720 align:middle line:90%
We come from the land.

00:37:43.720 --> 00:37:47.110 align:middle line:84%
And most people,
humans on the planet,

00:37:47.110 --> 00:37:49.180 align:middle line:84%
relate to land
one way or another

00:37:49.180 --> 00:37:50.405 align:middle line:90%
because they belong to it.

00:37:50.405 --> 00:37:53.520 align:middle line:84%
And they force their own
identity out of it as well.

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:57.280 align:middle line:84%
And that will always
continue to happen.

00:37:57.280 --> 00:38:01.440 align:middle line:84%
It's like a biological bond
between a mother and a child.

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:03.420 align:middle line:90%
You can't break it.

00:38:03.420 --> 00:38:07.840 align:middle line:84%
That bond is enforced when the
genealogy of the ancestors,

00:38:07.840 --> 00:38:12.250 align:middle line:84%
of their families, grandparents
is emotionally installed

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:14.840 align:middle line:84%
in that person, that they
feel that they belong here.

00:38:14.840 --> 00:38:23.670 align:middle line:90%


00:38:23.670 --> 00:38:26.270 align:middle line:84%
>> Interbeing is a
very natural term.

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:28.220 align:middle line:84%
It means more than
interconnection

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:32.690 align:middle line:84%
or interdependency, which kind
of suggests separate selves

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.320 align:middle line:90%
having relationships.

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:36.020 align:middle line:84%
Interbeing is more
of an understanding

00:38:36.020 --> 00:38:41.000 align:middle line:84%
that we are relationship, that
my very existence depends,

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.670 align:middle line:84%
or draws from, or
includes your existence.

00:38:43.670 --> 00:38:46.920 align:middle line:90%


00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:50.090 align:middle line:84%
My well-being is intimately
connected to your well-being

00:38:50.090 --> 00:38:56.180 align:middle line:84%
or to the well-being of the
river, the ocean, forest,

00:38:56.180 --> 00:38:59.210 align:middle line:84%
people across the world, and
so forth, because I'm not

00:38:59.210 --> 00:39:00.330 align:middle line:90%
really separate from you.

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:03.130 align:middle line:90%


00:39:03.130 --> 00:39:06.140 align:middle line:84%
And that means that in
the story of interbeing,

00:39:06.140 --> 00:39:08.840 align:middle line:84%
I know that whatever
I do to the world

00:39:08.840 --> 00:39:12.260 align:middle line:90%
will come back to me somehow.

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:16.580 align:middle line:84%
So if our true being is the
totality of our relationships

00:39:16.580 --> 00:39:19.910 align:middle line:84%
and includes everything
in the cosmos,

00:39:19.910 --> 00:39:23.520 align:middle line:84%
if we are truly maybe
a holographic mirror

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:27.880 align:middle line:84%
of all that is, then
when we cut ourselves off

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:32.770 align:middle line:84%
from any aspect of nature,
other people, we create a wound.

00:39:32.770 --> 00:39:34.780 align:middle line:90%
We create a cut off.

00:39:34.780 --> 00:39:37.720 align:middle line:90%
And this is painful.

00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:42.740 align:middle line:84%
And we yearn to
recover our wholeness.

00:39:42.740 --> 00:39:48.650 align:middle line:84%
However, due to ideology, due to
the economic system that we're

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:50.960 align:middle line:84%
immersed in, due to
cultural factors,

00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:57.010 align:middle line:84%
due to many, many, many reasons,
the reunion that we long for

00:39:57.010 --> 00:39:59.830 align:middle line:90%
is unavailable to us.

00:39:59.830 --> 00:40:04.077 align:middle line:84%
That is good for business,
because it drives consumerism.

00:40:04.077 --> 00:40:05.160 align:middle line:90%
It drives inquisitiveness.

00:40:05.160 --> 00:40:06.980 align:middle line:90%
It drives greed.

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:09.400 align:middle line:84%
It drives all kinds
of neurotic behaviors

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:13.540 align:middle line:84%
that seek to compensate for
the missing relationships.

00:40:13.540 --> 00:40:22.486 align:middle line:90%


