where the money supply really,
really gets chopped down,

00:52:16.850 --> 00:52:19.428 align:middle line:90%
people still have needs.

00:52:19.428 --> 00:52:20.970 align:middle line:84%
People still have
goods and services.

00:52:20.970 --> 00:52:24.260 align:middle line:84%
They're going to find a
way to exchange those.

00:52:24.260 --> 00:52:26.630 align:middle line:84%
What you want is the
easiest possible way

00:52:26.630 --> 00:52:28.650 align:middle line:90%
to make this happen.

00:52:28.650 --> 00:52:31.610 align:middle line:84%
And this is where alternative
currencies would plug the gap.

00:52:31.610 --> 00:52:35.840 align:middle line:84%
If a central government
were quick-thinking quick

00:52:35.840 --> 00:52:38.180 align:middle line:84%
off the mark and
actually had a plan

00:52:38.180 --> 00:52:40.010 align:middle line:84%
for dealing with
this stuff, they

00:52:40.010 --> 00:52:43.760 align:middle line:84%
could introduce a new currency,
maybe a parallel currency,

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:47.660 align:middle line:84%
maybe a replacement currency
to counteract the disappearance

00:52:47.660 --> 00:52:48.980 align:middle line:90%
of all the bank money.

00:52:48.980 --> 00:52:50.540 align:middle line:84%
That probably won't
happen, though.

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:54.200 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to be up to
local and regional currencies

00:52:54.200 --> 00:52:55.060 align:middle line:90%
to fill that void.

00:52:55.060 --> 00:53:04.530 align:middle line:90%


00:53:04.530 --> 00:53:08.430 align:middle line:84%
>> I woke up one morning and
jumped out of bed without even

00:53:08.430 --> 00:53:10.740 align:middle line:84%
being conscious yet, saying,
I'm going to start a local

00:53:10.740 --> 00:53:13.110 align:middle line:90%
currency.

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:15.150 align:middle line:90%
And I just felt so much joy.

00:53:15.150 --> 00:53:18.880 align:middle line:84%
There was just this
energy moving through me.

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:22.170 align:middle line:84%
LOAVES stands for Local Origin
Ashurst Voluntary Exchange

00:53:22.170 --> 00:53:23.250 align:middle line:90%
System.

00:53:23.250 --> 00:53:25.140 align:middle line:84%
It's one of those
acronyms that you

00:53:25.140 --> 00:53:27.480 align:middle line:84%
fit the words to the acronym
instead of the other way

00:53:27.480 --> 00:53:29.030 align:middle line:90%
around.

00:53:29.030 --> 00:53:32.510 align:middle line:84%
It is meant to be a
voucher system that

00:53:32.510 --> 00:53:35.240 align:middle line:84%
circulates in Ashurst
and the Pohangina Valley

00:53:35.240 --> 00:53:41.000 align:middle line:84%
as a voluntary alternative
to using money for exchange.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.850 align:middle line:84%
So LOAVES is primarily trading
at the Ashurst Community

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:47.000 align:middle line:84%
Market, and we have about
a dozen or so businesses

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:48.760 align:middle line:90%
that are accepting it there.

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:49.940 align:middle line:90%
We've got the cheesery.

00:53:49.940 --> 00:53:51.920 align:middle line:90%
We've got the fudgery.

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:53.930 align:middle line:84%
We have several
plant businesses.

00:53:53.930 --> 00:53:56.540 align:middle line:84%
We have a business
consultant who accepts it

00:53:56.540 --> 00:53:58.130 align:middle line:90%
outside of the market.

00:53:58.130 --> 00:54:02.660 align:middle line:84%
And there's half a dozen others
that are accepting it as well.

00:54:02.660 --> 00:54:06.620 align:middle line:84%
One of the primary benefits
of the currency in my mind

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:09.590 align:middle line:84%
is the awareness raising
that goes along with it.

00:54:09.590 --> 00:54:13.130 align:middle line:84%
We're after not the currency
itself but the relationships

00:54:13.130 --> 00:54:15.050 align:middle line:90%
that come out of the currency.

00:54:15.050 --> 00:54:17.900 align:middle line:84%
So one of the major things
is this awareness campaign

00:54:17.900 --> 00:54:21.650 align:middle line:84%
around the benefits of buying
local, the benefits of having

00:54:21.650 --> 00:54:24.760 align:middle line:84%
a commitment between
customers and businesses,

00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:27.780 align:middle line:84%
of knowing what's available
in your own community,

00:54:27.780 --> 00:54:29.880 align:middle line:84%
of going to town
instead of the city

00:54:29.880 --> 00:54:32.540 align:middle line:84%
when you need something, of
supporting your neighbors

00:54:32.540 --> 00:54:35.090 align:middle line:84%
and looking to your neighbors
and their businesses

00:54:35.090 --> 00:54:39.950 align:middle line:84%
as a primary way of
meeting your needs.

00:54:39.950 --> 00:54:44.030 align:middle line:84%
>> The wealth generated by
using our local currency--

00:54:44.030 --> 00:54:46.580 align:middle line:90%
100% of it stays here.

00:54:46.580 --> 00:54:48.730 align:middle line:84%
There's no interest,
and it just keeps

00:54:48.730 --> 00:54:53.240 align:middle line:84%
circulating and recirculating
in the local community.

00:54:53.240 --> 00:54:57.620 align:middle line:84%
And rather than being
considered in competition

00:54:57.620 --> 00:55:02.120 align:middle line:84%
with the national money, it's
actually complementary to it.

00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:06.210 align:middle line:90%


00:55:06.210 --> 00:55:09.150 align:middle line:84%
>> So you strengthen
these local connections.

00:55:09.150 --> 00:55:10.890 align:middle line:84%
Of course, that's a
very resilient thing

00:55:10.890 --> 00:55:14.370 align:middle line:84%
to do because it just means
that if things are rough,

00:55:14.370 --> 00:55:18.690 align:middle line:84%
you've got friends, neighbors,
and people in your region that

00:55:18.690 --> 00:55:20.400 align:middle line:84%
are able to help
one another out.

00:55:20.400 --> 00:55:23.630 align:middle line:90%


00:55:23.630 --> 00:55:26.330 align:middle line:84%
Time banking is a very
interesting development

00:55:26.330 --> 00:55:31.070 align:middle line:84%
in that it uses a very
egalitarian basis.

00:55:31.070 --> 00:55:34.400 align:middle line:84%
It says everybody's
time is equal.

00:55:34.400 --> 00:55:36.870 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't matter
how skilled you are

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:38.960 align:middle line:84%
or what your
qualifications are or what

00:55:38.960 --> 00:55:41.990 align:middle line:84%
you do for your day job,
that your hour is worth

00:55:41.990 --> 00:55:43.140 align:middle line:90%
the same as my hour.

00:55:43.140 --> 00:56:03.850 align:middle line:90%


00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:07.860 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm Maria Lee from Te Mahi
Kai at Diamond Harbour School,

00:56:07.860 --> 00:56:11.390 align:middle line:84%
which is a gardening
to cooking program.

00:56:11.390 --> 00:56:15.230 align:middle line:84%
So we teach the children how
to grow everything themselves.

00:56:15.230 --> 00:56:19.370 align:middle line:84%
And they put the seeds in
then look after the garden.

00:56:19.370 --> 00:56:21.890 align:middle line:84%
And then when it's my turn,
we harvest what they've

00:56:21.890 --> 00:56:24.260 align:middle line:90%
grown and turn it into lunch.

00:56:24.260 --> 00:56:31.290 align:middle line:90%


00:56:31.290 --> 00:56:35.580 align:middle line:84%
So today we're making kale
chips and broad bean dip.

00:56:35.580 --> 00:56:38.400 align:middle line:90%
And each week, it's different.

00:56:38.400 --> 00:56:41.280 align:middle line:84%
The idea is just to teach
them some basics of cooking.

00:56:41.280 --> 00:56:45.240 align:middle line:84%
And in order for that to work,
we use time bank volunteers.

00:56:45.240 --> 00:56:48.210 align:middle line:84%
And we couldn't do
it without them.

00:56:48.210 --> 00:56:51.880 align:middle line:84%
Our volunteers are
paid 1 credit per hour

00:56:51.880 --> 00:56:53.820 align:middle line:84%
that they come and
volunteer for us.

00:56:53.820 --> 00:56:58.080 align:middle line:84%
So we take those from the
school time bank credit system

00:56:58.080 --> 00:56:59.290 align:middle line:90%
and give it to them.

00:56:59.290 --> 00:57:01.890 align:middle line:84%
And then they use that to
trade for whatever they need.

00:57:01.890 --> 00:57:06.940 align:middle line:90%


00:57:06.940 --> 00:57:10.930 align:middle line:84%
>> It's always easier to build
your barn while the sun is

00:57:10.930 --> 00:57:14.110 align:middle line:84%
shining than try to put
it up in a howling gale.

00:57:14.110 --> 00:57:17.030 align:middle line:84%
So if you put these
things together now,

00:57:17.030 --> 00:57:19.510 align:middle line:84%
if you get a system up and
running, and especially

00:57:19.510 --> 00:57:21.010 align:middle line:84%
with something like
a local currency

00:57:21.010 --> 00:57:23.950 align:middle line:84%
where there may be some
marketing involved,

00:57:23.950 --> 00:57:26.080 align:middle line:84%
trying to get buy-in
from people and all

00:57:26.080 --> 00:57:29.000 align:middle line:84%
that-- you don't create one of
these things out of whole cloth

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:31.776 align:middle line:84%
and get it widely
accepted overnight.

00:57:31.776 --> 00:57:35.640 align:middle line:90%


00:57:35.640 --> 00:57:37.420 align:middle line:84%
>> But there's no
getting away from it.

00:57:37.420 --> 00:57:40.180 align:middle line:84%
A huge part of this is that we
just consume too much stuff.

00:57:40.180 --> 00:57:43.400 align:middle line:90%


00:57:43.400 --> 00:57:45.500 align:middle line:84%
Our entire economy
is built on getting

00:57:45.500 --> 00:57:49.535 align:middle line:84%
us to buy and consume,
dispose, and re-consume things.

00:57:49.535 --> 00:57:52.670 align:middle line:90%


00:57:52.670 --> 00:57:54.680 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it's
realistic that we can expect

00:57:54.680 --> 00:57:57.272 align:middle line:84%
to live in a world where we
don't make things or use things

00:57:57.272 --> 00:57:58.730 align:middle line:84%
or use resources--
of course we do.

00:57:58.730 --> 00:58:01.310 align:middle line:84%
But we need to use them
in a way that is smart.

00:58:01.310 --> 00:58:02.510 align:middle line:90%
It's about intelligent use.

00:58:02.510 --> 00:58:04.580 align:middle line:84%
It's about being efficient
and not wasteful.

00:58:04.580 --> 00:58:07.840 align:middle line:90%


00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:11.700 align:middle line:84%
>> The notion of waste is
something that wasn't around

00:58:11.700 --> 00:58:13.450 align:middle line:90%
200 or 300 years ago.

00:58:13.450 --> 00:58:14.570 align:middle line:90%
We just didn't have waste.

00:58:14.570 --> 00:58:16.180 align:middle line:90%
Things had utility.

00:58:16.180 --> 00:58:19.190 align:middle line:84%
Things have value
all the way through.

00:58:19.190 --> 00:58:23.410 align:middle line:84%
And if they reached the
end of productivity,

00:58:23.410 --> 00:58:26.140 align:middle line:84%
they were know reformed
into something else.

00:58:26.140 --> 00:58:32.390 align:middle line:90%


00:58:32.390 --> 00:58:35.790 align:middle line:84%
Welcome to Bayswater
Repair Cafe.

00:58:35.790 --> 00:58:39.530 align:middle line:84%
A repair cafe is a
free pop-up event

00:58:39.530 --> 00:58:45.290 align:middle line:84%
where local community experts
in a variety of different areas

00:58:45.290 --> 00:58:48.080 align:middle line:84%
offer their skills and
services to other people

00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:51.620 align:middle line:84%
in their local
community for free.

00:58:51.620 --> 00:58:55.380 align:middle line:84%
Every year we send a
crazy amount of stuff

00:58:55.380 --> 00:58:56.710 align:middle line:90%
to holes in the ground.

00:58:56.710 --> 00:58:59.780 align:middle line:84%
And this is about
maybe doing something

00:58:59.780 --> 00:59:02.030 align:middle line:84%
to address some of
that flow, but also

00:59:02.030 --> 00:59:04.280 align:middle line:84%
in the process of doing that,
bringing people together

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:08.330 align:middle line:84%
in a beautiful way
that connects people.

00:59:08.330 --> 00:59:13.490 align:middle line:84%
Create some networks and
maybe even some friendships.

00:59:13.490 --> 00:59:19.550 align:middle line:84%
So we've got five different
repair areas at the cafe today.

00:59:19.550 --> 00:59:22.760 align:middle line:84%
We've got our electrical
appliances repair space,

00:59:22.760 --> 00:59:25.640 align:middle line:84%
and that is overwhelmingly
the most popular area.

00:59:25.640 --> 00:59:29.180 align:middle line:84%
So people bring in toasters
and lamps and all kinds

00:59:29.180 --> 00:59:32.910 align:middle line:90%
of random bits and pieces.

00:59:32.910 --> 00:59:35.680 align:middle line:84%
We've got a clothing
repair space,

00:59:35.680 --> 00:59:40.280 align:middle line:84%
and we've got a team of
seamstresses and a seamster,

00:59:40.280 --> 00:59:43.955 align:middle line:84%
if that's the right word,
who are mending clothes.

00:59:43.955 --> 00:59:46.730 align:middle line:90%


00:59:46.730 --> 00:59:53.270 align:middle line:84%
We've got a guy who is repairing
wood and pieces of furniture.

00:59:53.270 --> 00:59:55.340 align:middle line:84%
And we've got general
repairs, and we've also

00:59:55.340 --> 00:59:56.930 align:middle line:90%
got two bike mechanics.

00:59:56.930 --> 00:59:59.580 align:middle line:90%


00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:03.100 align:middle line:84%
I was speaking to the daughter
of one of the volunteers who

01:00:03.100 --> 01:00:05.620 align:middle line:90%
helped out with repairs.

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:08.050 align:middle line:90%
And he was an older guy.

01:00:08.050 --> 01:00:15.520 align:middle line:84%
And he said to her that he
felt a real sense of belonging

01:00:15.520 --> 01:00:20.650 align:middle line:84%
and a real sense of feeling
useful and having purpose.

01:00:20.650 --> 01:00:24.660 align:middle line:84%
And I thought that was an
amazing outcome from the day,

01:00:24.660 --> 01:00:29.050 align:middle line:84%
to make someone feel
good about having shared

01:00:29.050 --> 01:00:33.700 align:middle line:90%
their skills with local people.

01:00:33.700 --> 01:00:36.520 align:middle line:84%
This is a beautiful example
of a community initiative

01:00:36.520 --> 01:00:40.900 align:middle line:84%
that brings people together
and enhances connection,

01:00:40.900 --> 01:00:43.960 align:middle line:84%
enhances a sense of
community and neighborhood.

01:00:43.960 --> 01:00:48.710 align:middle line:90%
And we fix a lot of stuff.

01:00:48.710 --> 01:00:50.710 align:middle line:84%
But more important
than that, I think,

01:00:50.710 --> 01:00:53.864 align:middle line:84%
is the building of
connection and community.

01:00:53.864 --> 01:00:58.810 align:middle line:90%


01:00:58.810 --> 01:01:01.500 align:middle line:84%
>> It's really important to
remember that when you dispose

01:01:01.500 --> 01:01:04.050 align:middle line:84%
of something, you
can't throw it away.

01:01:04.050 --> 01:01:07.545 align:middle line:84%
When you throw something,
it goes somewhere.

01:01:07.545 --> 01:01:08.920 align:middle line:84%
You might not know
where that is.

01:01:08.920 --> 01:01:11.128 align:middle line:84%
It may be out of your sight,
may be out of your mind.

01:01:11.128 --> 01:01:12.690 align:middle line:84%
But there is no
such place as away.

01:01:12.690 --> 01:01:17.690 align:middle line:90%


01:01:17.690 --> 01:01:20.900 align:middle line:84%
>> In 2007, we were really
starting to think about

01:01:20.900 --> 01:01:23.500 align:middle line:84%
our impacts that we were having,
just our regular day-to-day

01:01:23.500 --> 01:01:24.300 align:middle line:90%
actions.

01:01:24.300 --> 01:01:25.880 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
things we focused on

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:28.243 align:middle line:84%
was how much rubbish
we were producing.

01:01:28.243 --> 01:01:29.660 align:middle line:84%
We could have
focused on anything,

01:01:29.660 --> 01:01:31.580 align:middle line:90%
but rubbish was so visual.

01:01:31.580 --> 01:01:34.940 align:middle line:84%
And we're-- just every week
rubbish bags filling up.

01:01:34.940 --> 01:01:39.170 align:middle line:84%
And so we somehow decided
to challenge ourselves.

01:01:39.170 --> 01:01:41.180 align:middle line:84%
We can't even remember
whose idea it was now.

01:01:41.180 --> 01:01:43.610 align:middle line:84%
But we did this crazy thing
where we thought, right,

01:01:43.610 --> 01:01:48.330 align:middle line:84%
we're going to try and make no
rubbish for the entire year.

01:01:48.330 --> 01:01:51.560 align:middle line:84%
We were genuinely
not green people.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:54.200 align:middle line:84%
We were putting out a
bag of rubbish every week

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:55.520 align:middle line:90%
without fail.

01:01:55.520 --> 01:01:58.520 align:middle line:84%
And we had literally never
thought about it before.

01:01:58.520 --> 01:02:01.740 align:middle line:84%
We sort of-- it came to us
one day and went, oh my gosh,

01:02:01.740 --> 01:02:03.580 align:middle line:90%
this is terrible.

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:06.500 align:middle line:84%
>> In terms of the challenge
was to try and live for one year

01:02:06.500 --> 01:02:09.100 align:middle line:84%
with less than a city
council rubbish bag.

01:02:09.100 --> 01:02:11.410 align:middle line:84%
And most of it was
made up of items

01:02:11.410 --> 01:02:12.620 align:middle line:90%
that were out of our control.

01:02:12.620 --> 01:02:15.340 align:middle line:84%
So the radiator hose
on the car burst,

01:02:15.340 --> 01:02:17.028 align:middle line:90%
and so we had a radiator hose.

01:02:17.028 --> 01:02:19.570 align:middle line:84%
And we tried to carry on doing
things that you'd normally do.

01:02:19.570 --> 01:02:22.090 align:middle line:84%
So we were renovating
our home back then.

01:02:22.090 --> 01:02:25.330 align:middle line:84%
And we had all the lead paint
from scraping the weather

01:02:25.330 --> 01:02:26.945 align:middle line:90%
boards.

01:02:26.945 --> 01:02:29.070 align:middle line:84%
So in practical terms,
that's all we had left over.

01:02:29.070 --> 01:02:35.310 align:middle line:90%


01:02:35.310 --> 01:02:39.010 align:middle line:84%
I think when we look at the
average rubbish bin, what

01:02:39.010 --> 01:02:42.730 align:middle line:84%
people are putting out, at least
50% of it's generally organics.

01:02:42.730 --> 01:02:46.330 align:middle line:84%
And so you take the biggest
things out first, right?

01:02:46.330 --> 01:02:49.120 align:middle line:84%
So deal with organics
is the no-brainer.

01:02:49.120 --> 01:02:54.270 align:middle line:84%
If you do that, you're 50%
ahead of the average citizen.

01:02:54.270 --> 01:02:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And then there's another sort
of 30% of recyclable material

01:02:58.540 --> 01:03:01.600 align:middle line:84%
generally these days
in the rubbish bin.

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:02.760 align:middle line:90%
So there's the next thing.

01:03:02.760 --> 01:03:04.450 align:middle line:90%
So you deal with the organics.

01:03:04.450 --> 01:03:05.950 align:middle line:84%
Then you recycle
everything you can.

01:03:05.950 --> 01:03:08.740 align:middle line:84%
And you're getting up
in-- by that stage,

01:03:08.740 --> 01:03:11.770 align:middle line:90%
you've made massive gains.

01:03:11.770 --> 01:03:14.920 align:middle line:84%
People can feel overwhelmed and
feel that what they're doing

01:03:14.920 --> 01:03:16.840 align:middle line:90%
doesn't make a difference.

01:03:16.840 --> 01:03:22.060 align:middle line:84%
But most of the waste we create
or we're kind of complicit in

01:03:22.060 --> 01:03:24.100 align:middle line:90%
is waste we've never seen.

01:03:24.100 --> 01:03:25.890 align:middle line:84%
So we'll buy
something, and there'll

01:03:25.890 --> 01:03:28.370 align:middle line:84%
be a bit of packaging
around it that we see.

01:03:28.370 --> 01:03:31.420 align:middle line:84%
But in making that item, that's
when the bulk of the waste

01:03:31.420 --> 01:03:32.750 align:middle line:90%
is created.

01:03:32.750 --> 01:03:34.930 align:middle line:84%
So if you're putting
out a rubbish bag,

01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:38.560 align:middle line:84%
it actually represents
70 rubbish bags of waste

01:03:38.560 --> 01:03:41.020 align:middle line:84%
that you've never
seen that has gone

01:03:41.020 --> 01:03:44.260 align:middle line:90%
into making that bag of waste.

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:47.380 align:middle line:90%
Consumers have it tough, right?

01:03:47.380 --> 01:03:49.800 align:middle line:84%
A lot of money goes into
marketing and sending

01:03:49.800 --> 01:03:54.380 align:middle line:84%
the messages that you can buy
our compostable packaging,

01:03:54.380 --> 01:03:56.620 align:middle line:84%
and you're saving
the environment.

01:03:56.620 --> 01:03:59.020 align:middle line:84%
And of course, compostable
packaging in any landfill

01:03:59.020 --> 01:04:00.340 align:middle line:90%
is just as bad.

01:04:00.340 --> 01:04:03.010 align:middle line:84%
>> It's the sort of thing that
actually needs to be composted

01:04:03.010 --> 01:04:06.310 align:middle line:84%
at very hot temperatures, so
it really needs commercial

01:04:06.310 --> 01:04:10.300 align:middle line:90%
composting to be done properly.

01:04:10.300 --> 01:04:12.760 align:middle line:84%
And one of the biggest
problems in my business

01:04:12.760 --> 01:04:14.860 align:middle line:84%
that I have to go to
vendors and say, I'm sorry.

01:04:14.860 --> 01:04:16.510 align:middle line:84%
I know you've paid
more and you've

01:04:16.510 --> 01:04:20.920 align:middle line:84%
been promised that this is eco
and compostable by the person

01:04:20.920 --> 01:04:22.810 align:middle line:90%
that sold it to you.

01:04:22.810 --> 01:04:27.010 align:middle line:84%
But they didn't actually go and
do their product stewardship

01:04:27.010 --> 01:04:29.980 align:middle line:84%
and find out whether the
composting industry can take it

01:04:29.980 --> 01:04:31.858 align:middle line:90%
in every place.

01:04:31.858 --> 01:04:34.150 align:middle line:84%
>> I think we've actually
got consumers that want to do

01:04:34.150 --> 01:04:34.950 align:middle line:90%
the right thing.

01:04:34.950 --> 01:04:37.525 align:middle line:84%
We've got businesses that
are doing amazing stuff.

01:04:37.525 --> 01:04:39.400 align:middle line:84%
And we've got a government
completely missing

01:04:39.400 --> 01:04:43.780 align:middle line:84%
in action in terms of providing
a framework to encourage

01:04:43.780 --> 01:04:46.402 align:middle line:90%
those behaviors more and more.

01:04:46.402 --> 01:04:48.610 align:middle line:84%
>> So when you do buy a
container at the supermarket,

01:04:48.610 --> 01:04:50.622 align:middle line:84%
you make sure it's a
reusable container.

01:04:50.622 --> 01:04:52.330 align:middle line:84%
And then you wash it
out, and you take it

01:04:52.330 --> 01:04:54.070 align:middle line:84%
into one of these stores and
you get them to weigh it.

01:04:54.070 --> 01:04:55.780 align:middle line:84%
And then you fill it up
with whatever you want,

01:04:55.780 --> 01:04:57.170 align:middle line:90%
and they take the weight of it.

01:04:57.170 --> 01:05:01.190 align:middle line:84%
And you've just stopped
thick plastic packaging.

01:05:01.190 --> 01:05:03.440 align:middle line:84%
>> If people are combining
composting and learning how

01:05:03.440 --> 01:05:05.857 align:middle line:84%
to recycle and they're just
putting a bit of extra thought

01:05:05.857 --> 01:05:08.770 align:middle line:84%
into how they're shopping,
particularly considering that

01:05:08.770 --> 01:05:12.400 align:middle line:90%
packaging--

01:05:12.400 --> 01:05:15.720 align:middle line:84%
it's that choice when
you're at the supermarket

01:05:15.720 --> 01:05:20.340 align:middle line:84%
or at Bunnings or whatever,
thinking about the item,

01:05:20.340 --> 01:05:23.970 align:middle line:84%
essentially if it's plastic or
got other composite materials

01:05:23.970 --> 01:05:25.200 align:middle line:90%
in it.

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:27.100 align:middle line:84%
What can you do with
it at the end of life?

01:05:27.100 --> 01:05:27.900 align:middle line:90%
Not much.

01:05:27.900 --> 01:05:29.160 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be rubbish.

01:05:29.160 --> 01:05:32.470 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be around
for thousands of years.

01:05:32.470 --> 01:05:35.690 align:middle line:84%
Every time we spend a
dollar, it's a vote.

01:05:35.690 --> 01:05:37.570 align:middle line:84%
We have so much
power, so much more

01:05:37.570 --> 01:05:39.250 align:middle line:90%
power than what we realize.

01:05:39.250 --> 01:05:41.080 align:middle line:84%
So it's like keep
on that knife edge.

01:05:41.080 --> 01:05:43.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes, see that it's a big--

01:05:43.060 --> 01:05:44.140 align:middle line:90%
yes, there's big issues.

01:05:44.140 --> 01:05:46.968 align:middle line:84%
But also yes, we can
make a difference.

01:05:46.968 --> 01:05:49.490 align:middle line:90%


01:05:49.490 --> 01:05:53.680 align:middle line:84%
>> There's part of me when
I go to recycle my bottles

01:05:53.680 --> 01:05:59.830 align:middle line:84%
or compost my waste, it's like,
well, what good does it do?

01:05:59.830 --> 01:06:03.400 align:middle line:84%
I know I'm just subtracting
one plastic bottle

01:06:03.400 --> 01:06:07.910 align:middle line:84%
from the enormous trash heap
that gets shipped to India

01:06:07.910 --> 01:06:11.880 align:middle line:84%
and is making new mountains
in India and China of waste.

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:16.760 align:middle line:84%
Like, what does it matter,
one bottle different?

01:06:16.760 --> 01:06:19.190 align:middle line:84%
You can say, well,
if everybody did it,

01:06:19.190 --> 01:06:21.060 align:middle line:90%
then it would make a difference.

01:06:21.060 --> 01:06:22.460 align:middle line:90%
So you have to do your part.

01:06:22.460 --> 01:06:26.740 align:middle line:84%
But part of you will say,
well, I'm not everybody.

01:06:26.740 --> 01:06:30.570 align:middle line:84%
And if everybody does it, then
it doesn't matter if I do it.

01:06:30.570 --> 01:06:32.810 align:middle line:84%
So you have to have
another reason.

01:06:32.810 --> 01:06:36.740 align:middle line:84%
For me, it comes down to
relationship and ritual.

01:06:36.740 --> 01:06:41.000 align:middle line:84%
I like to save my compost
and use composting toilets,

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:47.570 align:middle line:84%
for example, not because I've
done some calculation that this

01:06:47.570 --> 01:06:50.330 align:middle line:84%
is going to save the
world, but because it's

01:06:50.330 --> 01:06:53.870 align:middle line:84%
a different kind of relationship
with the beings around me.

01:06:53.870 --> 01:07:02.570 align:middle line:90%


01:07:02.570 --> 01:07:05.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Composting toilets, like
composting your own shit,

01:07:05.320 --> 01:07:07.750 align:middle line:84%
processing your
own toilet waste,

01:07:07.750 --> 01:07:10.370 align:middle line:84%
is a real basic fundamental
thing that we should all

01:07:10.370 --> 01:07:11.170 align:middle line:90%
practice.

01:07:11.170 --> 01:07:16.580 align:middle line:84%
It's a simple way
of demonstrating

01:07:16.580 --> 01:07:18.860 align:middle line:90%
self-responsibility.

01:07:18.860 --> 01:07:22.130 align:middle line:84%
>> So with a flush toilet,
basically you take really nice

01:07:22.130 --> 01:07:27.760 align:middle line:84%
clean drinking water and a
shit and mix the two together,

01:07:27.760 --> 01:07:29.210 align:middle line:90%
both wonderful resources.

01:07:29.210 --> 01:07:33.440 align:middle line:84%
When you mix them together,
you create a toxic problem.

01:07:33.440 --> 01:07:36.800 align:middle line:84%
So with a compost
toilet system, you're

01:07:36.800 --> 01:07:41.600 align:middle line:84%
able to capture that amazing
resource and take care of it

01:07:41.600 --> 01:07:45.620 align:middle line:84%
and treat it in a way
that removes any pathogens

01:07:45.620 --> 01:07:47.795 align:middle line:84%
or problems and create
a wonderful resource.

01:07:47.795 --> 01:07:52.460 align:middle line:90%


01:07:52.460 --> 01:07:54.980 align:middle line:90%
>> OK, so welcome to our toilet.

01:07:54.980 --> 01:07:57.860 align:middle line:84%
For a start, it's a composting
toilet bucket bench system.

01:07:57.860 --> 01:08:00.080 align:middle line:84%
We've got cover
material which we

01:08:00.080 --> 01:08:02.930 align:middle line:90%
use old sawdust from the mill.

01:08:02.930 --> 01:08:05.600 align:middle line:84%
It's already got bacteria
and bit of fungus in it.

01:08:05.600 --> 01:08:08.990 align:middle line:84%
So you go make your deposit,
put a bit of cover material

01:08:08.990 --> 01:08:10.640 align:middle line:90%
on, leave it.

01:08:10.640 --> 01:08:12.920 align:middle line:84%
And then when we've got a
certain amount of buckets,

01:08:12.920 --> 01:08:16.580 align:middle line:84%
we go to the compost and
add straw and garden waste

01:08:16.580 --> 01:08:17.420 align:middle line:90%
and kitchen waste.

01:08:17.420 --> 01:08:21.240 align:middle line:90%


01:08:21.240 --> 01:08:23.779 align:middle line:84%
And this is one I
did maybe a week ago.

01:08:23.779 --> 01:08:26.720 align:middle line:84%
And we'll put the compost
thermometer in here

01:08:26.720 --> 01:08:28.220 align:middle line:90%
and see what we're looking at.

01:08:28.220 --> 01:08:30.399 align:middle line:84%
We're still looking
at 50 degrees.

01:08:30.399 --> 01:08:31.529 align:middle line:90%
It's going up.

01:08:31.529 --> 01:08:33.740 align:middle line:84%
It got up to 65
degrees the other day.

01:08:33.740 --> 01:08:34.877 align:middle line:90%
I recorded it a bit.

01:08:34.877 --> 01:08:36.710 align:middle line:84%
>> There are pathogens
you have to consider.

01:08:36.710 --> 01:08:39.859 align:middle line:84%
There's roundworm eggs and
all these different kinds

01:08:39.859 --> 01:08:44.660 align:middle line:84%
of worm eggs that can
exist in your manure.

01:08:44.660 --> 01:08:47.330 align:middle line:84%
But if you do a hot compost,
that's the safest way.

01:08:47.330 --> 01:08:51.020 align:middle line:84%
Because you can nuke all
those things within hours.

01:08:51.020 --> 01:08:54.170 align:middle line:90%


01:08:54.170 --> 01:09:02.600 align:middle line:84%
>> And over here
is what you get.

01:09:02.600 --> 01:09:07.109 align:middle line:84%
I put it in a bag,
but you don't need to.

01:09:07.109 --> 01:09:09.950 align:middle line:90%
That there is about a year old.

01:09:09.950 --> 01:09:12.060 align:middle line:90%
It's got lots of worms in it.

01:09:12.060 --> 01:09:17.200 align:middle line:84%
We put all our garden waste and
all our kitchen waste in here.

01:09:17.200 --> 01:09:18.450 align:middle line:90%
But the worms are a good sign.

01:09:18.450 --> 01:09:21.666 align:middle line:84%
If you've got worms, it means
it's not too acidic and mm,

01:09:21.666 --> 01:09:23.630 align:middle line:90%
yum, good stuff.

01:09:23.630 --> 01:09:26.970 align:middle line:84%
And that goes straight on the
garden, and the plants love it.

01:09:26.970 --> 01:09:28.189 align:middle line:90%
And we love the plants.

01:09:28.189 --> 01:09:31.185 align:middle line:90%


01:09:31.185 --> 01:09:32.560 align:middle line:84%
>> When it's
finished composting,

01:09:32.560 --> 01:09:36.220 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't look like or
smell like anything like poo.

01:09:36.220 --> 01:09:39.579 align:middle line:84%
It's just beautiful
black compost.

01:09:39.579 --> 01:09:41.149 align:middle line:90%
So we've monitored it closely.

01:09:41.149 --> 01:09:42.399 align:middle line:90%
We've watched the temperature.

01:09:42.399 --> 01:09:45.910 align:middle line:84%
We know all the pathogens
have been nuked.

01:09:45.910 --> 01:09:48.850 align:middle line:84%
We feel confident
in our process.

01:09:48.850 --> 01:09:52.270 align:middle line:84%
So we feel safe to
use it in our garden.

01:09:52.270 --> 01:09:53.810 align:middle line:90%
Anyone can do this.

01:09:53.810 --> 01:09:57.160 align:middle line:84%
It's just really a matter of
being engaged and wanting to do

01:09:57.160 --> 01:09:58.660 align:middle line:90%
it and getting the knowledge.

01:09:58.660 --> 01:10:00.700 align:middle line:90%
It's a knowledge-based system.

01:10:00.700 --> 01:10:03.970 align:middle line:84%
It's not technological or
anything really advanced.

01:10:03.970 --> 01:10:06.170 align:middle line:84%
I've seen people do it
in cities with a wee

01:10:06.170 --> 01:10:09.740 align:middle line:90%
backyard, small backyard, yeah.

01:10:09.740 --> 01:10:12.280 align:middle line:84%
And I've seen people do it
in really rural settings.

01:10:12.280 --> 01:10:15.010 align:middle line:84%
It's just a matter
of being engaged.

01:10:15.010 --> 01:10:19.330 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, it's for everyone,
everyone who wants to take more

01:10:19.330 --> 01:10:23.810 align:middle line:84%
responsibility for themselves
and not pass it off,

01:10:23.810 --> 01:10:25.060 align:middle line:90%
everyone who values their poo.

01:10:25.060 --> 01:10:29.590 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS] I value my poo.

01:10:29.590 --> 01:10:32.890 align:middle line:90%


01:10:32.890 --> 01:10:36.280 align:middle line:84%
I value your poo to, so
you're welcome to leave

01:10:36.280 --> 01:10:37.480 align:middle line:90%
a deposit before you go.

01:10:37.480 --> 01:10:40.130 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of expected
actually, no pressure.

01:10:40.130 --> 01:10:52.890 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

01:10:52.890 --> 01:10:55.160 align:middle line:84%
>> We've come to see
that in order to be part

01:10:55.160 --> 01:10:58.850 align:middle line:84%
of the solution, we really need
to use our everyday choices

01:10:58.850 --> 01:11:01.220 align:middle line:90%
to change our behavior.

01:11:01.220 --> 01:11:02.720 align:middle line:84%
And it's a cultural
shift that needs

01:11:02.720 --> 01:11:05.870 align:middle line:84%
to happen in order for us to at
least sustain ourselves, which

01:11:05.870 --> 01:11:09.210 align:middle line:84%
isn't even enough
of course because,

01:11:09.210 --> 01:11:11.352 align:middle line:90%
what are we sustaining?

01:11:11.352 --> 01:11:12.810 align:middle line:84%
And so that's
something I've really

01:11:12.810 --> 01:11:14.477 align:middle line:84%
been putting a lot
of time into recently

01:11:14.477 --> 01:11:17.660 align:middle line:84%
is designing my work so that
it's actually regenerative.

01:11:17.660 --> 01:11:25.160 align:middle line:90%


01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:27.480 align:middle line:84%
Sort of out of necessity I
started this organic waste

01:11:27.480 --> 01:11:28.280 align:middle line:90%
collection.

01:11:28.280 --> 01:11:30.542 align:middle line:90%
Check this out, whoa!

01:11:30.542 --> 01:11:33.290 align:middle line:90%


01:11:33.290 --> 01:11:36.260 align:middle line:84%
Here we're currently
picking about 2 and 1/2 tons

01:11:36.260 --> 01:11:38.330 align:middle line:84%
up each week from
local businesses.

01:11:38.330 --> 01:11:41.650 align:middle line:84%
And instead of that all going
into a hole in the ground,

01:11:41.650 --> 01:11:44.180 align:middle line:84%
it gets returned
back to the soil

01:11:44.180 --> 01:11:49.210 align:middle line:84%
by way of windrow
aerobic composting.

01:11:49.210 --> 01:11:53.050 align:middle line:84%
So we currently have
around 45 businesses

01:11:53.050 --> 01:11:54.590 align:middle line:90%
on the Why Waste collection.

01:11:54.590 --> 01:11:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And they have a number of bins
or buckets, mostly wheelie

01:11:58.190 --> 01:12:03.560 align:middle line:84%
bins, and some have up to five
wheelie bins at their business.

01:12:03.560 --> 01:12:07.070 align:middle line:84%
And every week Why Waste
comes and picks it up,

01:12:07.070 --> 01:12:08.690 align:middle line:90%
and we take it to--

01:12:08.690 --> 01:12:10.940 align:middle line:84%
we weigh it, we record all
the data, things like that.

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:13.460 align:middle line:84%
We take it to a
composting facility.

01:12:13.460 --> 01:12:16.520 align:middle line:84%
And so yeah, we're in
partnership with them

01:12:16.520 --> 01:12:21.900 align:middle line:84%
so that we can return that
waste back to the soil.

01:12:21.900 --> 01:12:23.695 align:middle line:84%
Recently, one of my
clients rang me up.

01:12:23.695 --> 01:12:25.320 align:middle line:84%
And they were super
stoked because they

01:12:25.320 --> 01:12:29.160 align:middle line:84%
were able to cancel
this big, like, skip bin

01:12:29.160 --> 01:12:31.200 align:middle line:90%
for their rubbish.

01:12:31.200 --> 01:12:34.650 align:middle line:84%
And now they just use a
240-liter wheelie bin,

01:12:34.650 --> 01:12:36.400 align:middle line:90%
which is much, much smaller.

01:12:36.400 --> 01:12:41.790 align:middle line:84%
And that's as a result of all
of their compostable waste

01:12:41.790 --> 01:12:44.100 align:middle line:90%
going back to the soil.

01:12:44.100 --> 01:12:45.543 align:middle line:90%
Oh, what's that?

01:12:45.543 --> 01:12:47.467 align:middle line:90%
Oh, a tasty muffin!

01:12:47.467 --> 01:12:52.770 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

01:12:52.770 --> 01:12:54.900 align:middle line:84%
I'm really passionate
about composting

01:12:54.900 --> 01:12:57.300 align:middle line:84%
as a solution of
minimizing our waste

01:12:57.300 --> 01:13:03.450 align:middle line:84%
and our impact here on this
one planet that we have.

01:13:03.450 --> 01:13:06.330 align:middle line:84%
Food scraps and
biodegradable waste

01:13:06.330 --> 01:13:10.530 align:middle line:84%
takes up over a third of
what we send to landfill.

01:13:10.530 --> 01:13:16.200 align:middle line:84%
When biodegradable matter
biodegrades anaerobically,

01:13:16.200 --> 01:13:18.060 align:middle line:84%
it produces a lot
of methane, which

01:13:18.060 --> 01:13:23.390 align:middle line:84%
is 23 times worse than carbon
dioxide as a greenhouse gas.

01:13:23.390 --> 01:13:27.910 align:middle line:84%
And not only do you get that
gas going into the atmosphere,

01:13:27.910 --> 01:13:31.050 align:middle line:84%
but you also get
a liquid version

01:13:31.050 --> 01:13:34.665 align:middle line:84%
of it leaching into our
soils, into our water table.

01:13:34.665 --> 01:13:37.470 align:middle line:90%


01:13:37.470 --> 01:13:39.590 align:middle line:84%
So what we're trying
to achieve here

01:13:39.590 --> 01:13:44.300 align:middle line:84%
is build a really hot
compost around this drum

01:13:44.300 --> 01:13:45.790 align:middle line:90%
and also all of this--

01:13:45.790 --> 01:13:48.710 align:middle line:84%
build all this
irrigation into it

01:13:48.710 --> 01:13:52.460 align:middle line:84%
so that when that aerobic
hot compost heats up,

01:13:52.460 --> 01:13:57.530 align:middle line:84%
we should be able to pump
water through the system

01:13:57.530 --> 01:14:01.710 align:middle line:84%
out and over to these
bathtubs over here

01:14:01.710 --> 01:14:08.760 align:middle line:84%
and have free
biologically-heated hot water.

01:14:08.760 --> 01:14:11.180 align:middle line:84%
The reason why I'm so
enthusiastic about compost

01:14:11.180 --> 01:14:14.630 align:middle line:84%
is that it's fertility
in its purest form.

01:14:14.630 --> 01:14:18.350 align:middle line:84%
This is how nature
builds soil, and that

01:14:18.350 --> 01:14:21.540 align:middle line:90%
enables us to grow more food.

01:14:21.540 --> 01:14:25.683 align:middle line:84%
And if people are
conscious of composting,

01:14:25.683 --> 01:14:28.100 align:middle line:84%
they're probably going to
become more conscious about what

01:14:28.100 --> 01:14:29.450 align:middle line:90%
they're eating.

01:14:29.450 --> 01:14:31.310 align:middle line:84%
And if they're
opening less packets,

01:14:31.310 --> 01:14:32.900 align:middle line:90%
that's good for everyone.

01:14:32.900 --> 01:14:34.290 align:middle line:90%
That's good for the planet.

01:14:34.290 --> 01:14:36.470 align:middle line:90%
It's good for our people.

01:14:36.470 --> 01:14:39.380 align:middle line:84%
If we can get people to
focus on eating better,

01:14:39.380 --> 01:14:42.980 align:middle line:84%
then we're actually able to
produce a lot less landfill

01:14:42.980 --> 01:14:46.730 align:middle line:84%
waste and a lot more
biodegradable waste, which

01:14:46.730 --> 01:14:50.210 align:middle line:84%
then can be turned into more
fertility to produce more food.

01:14:50.210 --> 01:14:54.560 align:middle line:84%
So the healthier we eat, the
better our waste is and much

01:14:54.560 --> 01:14:56.330 align:middle line:84%
easier to manage and
return to the land.

01:14:56.330 --> 01:14:59.850 align:middle line:90%


01:14:59.850 --> 01:15:05.010 align:middle line:84%
People talk about thinking
global, acting local.

01:15:05.010 --> 01:15:08.700 align:middle line:84%
I suppose I'm really sitting
in that truth presently.

01:15:08.700 --> 01:15:10.370 align:middle line:84%
I'd rather think
global and act global,

01:15:10.370 --> 01:15:13.460 align:middle line:84%
but we've got to start
somewhere, you know?

01:15:13.460 --> 01:15:17.973 align:middle line:84%
